I prefer<p><pre><code>    {|el| el + 5}
</code></pre>
more than<p><pre><code>    { _ + 5 }
</code></pre>
the latter is too implicit for my taste, also I imagine it could become more confusing in a more complex context.

I disagree that it maps most directly to the problem statement.  You&#x27;re performing a common factor computation in your mind, which may be more difficult given numbers other than 3 and 5. In my opinion, pattern matching offers the most direct solution and comes with an abundance of compiler optimizations.  Here&#x27;s an example in Rust...<p><pre><code>        for i in range(1i, 101) {  
            match (i % 3, i % 5) {  
                (0, 0) => println!(&quot;Fizzbuzz&quot;),  
                (0, _) => println!(&quot;Fizz&quot;),  
                (_, 0) => println!(&quot;Buzz&quot;),  
                _ => println!(&quot;{}&quot;, i),  
            }  
        }</code></pre>
